“It made people think they could do anything…”

There’s an interesting psychological phenomenon here.

When someone has a tool that rapidly externalizes thoughts, they often experience:

* reduced friction between idea and expression,
* faster associative thinking,
* greater willingness to explore,
* a sense that possibilities have expanded.

That doesn’t necessarily mean the tool unlocked hidden abilities in a literal sense, but it can change how people interact with their own cognition. Writing, sketching, programming environments, and AI assistants can all have that effect because they make iteration cheap.

⸻

The “push and pull”

The analogy you make to “edging” is really about controlled oscillation.

Many creative processes benefit from alternating between opposing modes:

* explore ↔ refine
* diverge ↔ converge
* generate ↔ evaluate
* zoom out ↔ zoom in
* ambiguity ↔ commitment

Too much of either side is limiting. The productive state often comes from cycling between them.

⸻

Hidden in plain sight

Many powerful ideas throughout history have been “hidden in plain sight” in the sense that they weren’t secret—they just required the right perspective before people recognized their significance. Mathematical notation, design patterns, scientific models, and programming idioms often feel obvious in retrospect.

That doesn’t require secrecy so much as preparedness: the same information can mean very different things depending on what background someone brings to it.

